@node "About" "About XPKatana"

    One nice thing about the Amiga is those Amiga-standards established by
various programmers.  XPK is one of them: it allows the end-user to use an
external packer which suits his system resources and needs, and it allows
the application programmer to easily add file compression capacities to his
file loading/saving routines.

   But one thing XPK was missing was a COMPLETE interface/server.  Oh for
sure, there are things like XDrop for the Workbench user, or PackX for the
CLI fanatic.  But how about those in-between who wants the power of the
Shell interface along with the ease of use of the XDrop AppIcon?   Or how
about those who wants to be able to pack/unpack files from other
applications but doesn't want to use a system patch?  Here comes XPKatana.

   XPKatana is a program with a complete GUI which will allow you to easily
pack and unpack files using the XPK system.  It also has a complete ARexx
port, allowing you to interface it with other applications.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"
@{b}XPKatana features:@{ub}

   @{b}°@{ub} Supports about every XPK packers and features such as encryption, 
     multi-mode packers, etc...

   @{b}°@{ub} Can unpack files packed with non-XPK packers, via @{"xfdmaster.library" link "About_Xfdmaster" 0}.

   @{b}°@{ub} Complete, Style-Guide compliant GUI, which doesn't need an
     external library.                                  

   @{b}°@{ub} Helps you to decide which packer to use by analyzing the source's 
     filetype (thanks to @{"FileID.library" link "About_FileID" 0}!)

   @{b}°@{ub} Complete ARexx port, allowing you to interface XPK with any other 
     application which has an ARexx port, providing XPK support to them.

   @{b}°@{ub} Allows for automated batch packing/unpacking via ARexx scripts.

   @{b}°@{ub} Script Record mode, allowing you to record your actions to a script 
     for easy script generation.

   @{b}°@{ub} Special "Test Mode": allows you to try a selected list of packers on a
     given file to determine which one is the best.  Also able to generate a
     report in a text file about the packing figures.

   @{b}°@{ub} ...And still more!
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"
   To work, XPKatana requires:

      @{b}°@{ub} Amiga OS 3.0 or higher;
      @{b}°@{ub} The XPK User archive, version 5.0 or higher.  This is available
        from Aminet (util/pack/xpk_User.lha)

   Also @{b}STRONGLY@{ub} recommended:

     @{b}°@{ub} ARexx
     @{b}°@{ub} @{"FileID.library" link "About_FileID" 0} by Oliver Lange (for file type identification, 
       included in the archive, but still optional for those with a 
       floppy-based system, who can't afford the disk space).
     @{b}°@{ub} @{"Xfdmaster.library" link "About_Xfdmaster" 0} (V37 or better) by Dirk Stoecker, to be able to
       unpack alien packers.  Not included in this archive, and
       totally optional.
     @{b}°@{ub} A hard disk.
     @{b}°@{ub} At least 1 Meg of memory.
     @{b}°@{ub} At least a 68020.  Not for XPKatana itself, but for the packers.  
       File compression will benefit a LOT from a simple 68020.
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"
   In the @{b}Install/@{ub} drawer you'll find various installation scripts for
XPKatana.  These require Commodore's Installer.

   If you don't have Installer, you can easily install XPKatana manually:

@{b}1)@{ub} Copy the main executable (XPKatana) in the directory of your choice
   (example: @{b}Utilities/@{ub} on your Workbench).

@{b}2)@{ub} Copy the FileID.library in the @{b}Libs:@{ub} directory of your Workbench if you
   want XPKatana to be able to identify the submitted files, giving you a
   better idea of the packer to use to pack the given file.  This library
   is optional, so you can skip that step if you are short in space on
   your Workbench.

@{b}3)@{ub} Copy the @{b}ARexx/@{ub} scripts in the directory where you usually keep the 
   other scripts (usually where the @{b}REXX:@{ub} assign points, or the @{b}s/@{ub}
   directory on your Workbench.  Included scripts are:

   @{b}Examine_kat.rexx
   Pack_kat.rexx
   Unpack_kat.rexx@{ub}

   These one allows you to examine, pack or unpack a given file from the Shell
with XPKatana running in background.  Read them to learn how to use them.

   @{b}FW-Pack_kat.rexx
   FW-Unpack_kat.rexx@{ub}

   These two scripts allows the @{i}Final Writer 4@{ui} users (from Softwood) to add
XPK support to files created by this excellent word processor.  Note that
these scripts should be easily adaptable for other products from Softwood.

   @{b}DO5-Pack_kat.rexx
   DO5-Unpack_kat.rexx@{ub}

   These two scripts adds XPK support to @{i}Directory Opus 5@{ui} (from GP
Software).

   @{b}DefIcons_kat.rexx@{ub}

   This script allow the user of DefIcons (distributed with NewIcons) to
use XPKatana as the default tool for compressed files.

   These ARexx scripts are optional, so you can skip that step if you don't
need them.
@endnode

@node "Workbench_Usage" "Workbench Usage"

   XPKatana can be launched from Workbench or from the Shell.  Here's a list
of supported tooltypes/command line options:


   @{b}DEFAULTDIR@{ub}: This is the default directory that will be used in the 
               file requester when selecting source.  Defaults to the 
               current directory.

   @{b}ICONIFY@{ub}   : Tells XPKatana to start in an iconified state.

   @{b}ICONX@{ub}     : Specify the "x" position of the AppIcon.

   @{b}ICONY@{ub}     : Specify the "y" position of the AppIcon.

   @{b}PUBSCREEN @{ub}: Tells XPKatana on which public screen it should open the 
               GUI.  Defaults to your default public screen.

   Note that XPKatana no longer reads its ToolType settings when launched from
the Shell.  This is a change from previous versions of XPKatana.

@endnode

@node "Main_Window" "Main Window"

    A quick view of the main window:

    - Across the top, the main processing gadgets:

    @{b}Process:@{ub} Click on this gadget to process the current source file using
        the Operation selected to the right.  The source file will be over-
        written with the new file with the same filename, unless you have
        "@{"Handle Suffix" link "Menu_Prefs" 45}" selected, in which case the .xpk suffix will be
        added or removed, depending if you're packing or unpacking the file.

    @{b}Process As...:@{ub} This is the same as "Process", except that a file
        requester will be opened, asking you to select the destination
        directory and filename.  The source file won't be affected, unless
        you have "@{"Delete Source" link "Menu_Prefs" 49}" selected in the preferences.

    @{b}Operation:@{ub} This cycle gadget lets you select which type of operation 
        you wish to perform on the source file.  Can be:

            @{b}° Pack@{ub} - Will compress the file using the current packer.

            @{b}° Unpack@{ub} - Will unpack the file with the required packer, no need
                for you to select which packer to use.  If the file is packed
                with a non-XPK packer and you have "@{"Unpack Alien" link "Menu_Prefs" 70}" enabled,
                XPKatana will try to unpack the file by using xfdmaster.library
                (which must be installed of your system).

            @{b}° Repack@{ub} - If the file is already packed, will unpack it before
                packing with the selected packer.

            @{b}° Test@{ub}  - Test a given selection of packers on the current source
                file.  See the section on @{"Testing" link "Test_Packers" 0}

    - Just below these, a string gadget labelled "Source:".  You can select the
    source file by entering it directly into the string gadget, or by clicking
    on the "Get..." button, which will open a file requestor.  You can also
    drag icons and drop them in the window to select them as the source.

    - Below that, to the left, is various information about the current source
    file:

    @{b}File Type:@{ub} This area tells you what type of file is currently
        selected as the source, according to FileID.library.  If
        FileID.library cannot be opened, this field will not be present.

    @{b}File Size:@{ub} This is the size in bytes of the source file.

    @{b}Packer:@{ub} If the file is packed, displays the packer used if it's a
        standard XPK packer, or "@{b}alien@{ub}" if it's a non-XPK packer.
        If the file is also encrypted, an "@{b}*@{ub}" will be added to the
        packer name.

    @{b}Unpacked Size:@{ub} Displays the size of the source file when unpacked (only
        for XPK-based packers), as well as the compression ratio.


    - Next to that, on the right, is the list of available packers.  You may
    select which packer to use by clicking on it, or use the cursor keys to
    scroll through the list.  You can configure the settings for the selected
    packer by clicking the @{"Set..." link "Set_Packer_Win" 0} button, or double-clicking the packer
    name in the list.

    - Across the bottom is the @{b}Status@{ub} bar.  This contains information
    about the current state of XPKatana, and about actions that are currently
    being performed.

@endnode

@node "Test_Packers" "Test Packers"
    When processing in "Test Mode", a new window will be opened, with two
listviews.  The left list holds all the available packers on your system,
while the right list holds the selected packers.  Select a packer on the
left list by double-clicking on it, or remove it by double-clicking on it in
the right list.

    On the right side, a column of buttons are available:

    @{b}About:@{ub} Display informations about the last packer you clicked on in
        any of the listviews (that packer's name is shown just below
        the "About" button).

    @{b}All/Clear:@{ub} Select all packers for testing, or clear the selected list.

    @{b}Test:@{ub} Launch the test procedure.

    @{b}Abort:@{ub} Abort the whole thing (clicking on the window's close gadget
        has the same effect).

     
    At the bottom of the window there's a @{b}"Output..."@{ub} button.  If you want
XPKatana to generate a complete report of the results in a text file, click
there to select the filename for the output file where the generated report
will be written.

    When you click on @{b}"Test"@{ub}, XPKatana will try each of the selected packers
on the source file.  When finished, it will tell you which packer gave  the
best compression ratio, with the ratio attained.  Then, you can select  the
"Pack" operation, select that packer in the packer list, and process the
file as usual.

    Note that while in Test mode, the source file @{b}WON'T@{ub} be modified.  This
mode will only let you "test" a given selection of packers on a file, without
affecting that file.
@endnode

@node "Set_Packer_Win" "Set Packer Window"
    This window is separated into three main parts:

    @{u}1) The packer information.@{uu}  In this area will be displayed a short
    description of the current packer (the name is displayed as the 
    window title), with informations about the packer's supported options:

    The @{b}maximum supported chunk size@{ub}.

    The @{b}default chunk size@{ub}.

    @{b}Encryption:@{ub} Does this packer allows encryption (and the use of a
        password, by the same time)?

    @{b}Lossy:@{ub} Does this packer does lossy compression?  Be careful about
        this.  Lossy compression can result in lost data for files
        which need to preserve their EXACT contents, such as text files
        or programs.  Could be acceptable for files, such as RAW sound
        samples, when losing some quality is okay to you.  You can
        prevent accidentally using a lossy packer by disabling them in
        the "@{"Preferences" link "Menu_Prefs" }".


    @{u}2) The packer settings.@{uu}

    @{b}Chunk Size:@{ub} The size (in bytes) of each block of data while packing.
        It also determines how often the progress window will be
        updated while packing a file.  Adjusting this might be
        useful if you're short in memory, or if you want to
        fine tune the packing efficiency.

        IMPORTANT: The Chunk size will be reset to the default
                   each time a new packer is selected!  This is
                   done to avoid problems since each packers have
                   different limits for this value.

    @{b}Password:@{ub} If you want to encrypt or decrypt a file, you must supply 
        a password.  Note that you will also have to enable the
        "@{"Use Password" link "Menu_Prefs" 37}" flag in the Prefs menu.


    @{u}3) The packer mode.@{uu}  Many packers support more than one packing mode.
    This is where you will adjust the desired @{b}packing mode@{ub}, depending on 
    the ratio vs speed issue desired.  The slider allows you to select the 
    desired packing mode, between 0 and 100, 100 giving the best 
    compression but the slowest (un)packing.  

    Note that the packmodes are usualy implemented as "steps".  For example:
A given packer can give you a fast but loose compression from 0-25, a cheap
compression from 26-50, average compression from  51-75, and the best
compression from 76-100.  So any value between each boundaries of a given
mode will give you the same result.  Check the mode name just above the
slider to determine the current mode.

    Just below there is some average specs about the current mode, in terms
of speed and memory usage for both packing and unpacking.

    Clicking on the close gadget will close the window, and return you to
the main window.
@endnode

@node "Progress_Window" "The Progress Window"
   While processing, a progress window will be opened, showing you various
informations about the current processing.

  Note that if the @{"No Progress" link "Menu_Prefs" 58} flag is enabled, the Progress Window won't be
opened.  If the main window is opened, minimal informations will be shown in
the status gadget about the processing's progress.

  In the progress window, you'll see:

  @{b}°@{ub} The filename being processed
  @{b}°@{ub} The processing type (and the destination filename)

  @{b}°@{ub} The packer's name

  @{b}°@{ub} The packer's efficiency  - 0% = No compression, 100% = whole file
    packed into a single byte :)
  @{b}°@{ub} How much of the processing has been completed so far

  @{b}°@{ub} The source's length in bytes
  @{b}°@{ub} How many bytes have been read from the source so far
  @{b}°@{ub} How many bytes have been written to the destination so far
  @{b}°@{ub} The Bytes Per Second (bps) speed ratio

   This progress window will get updated between each data chunks, as set
in the @{"Set Packer" link "Set_Packer_Win" 23} window.

   During processing, you can click on the @{b}"Abort"@{ub} gadget to stop processing.
Note that due to a limitation in XPK itself, processing can only be aborted
between each chunk, so it may take a few seconds before your Abort click gets
acknowledged.

   When processing is completed, click on the window's close gadget to close it.
@endnode

@node "Menus" "Menus"

   Attached to the main window of XPKatana, you'll find three menus:


  @{" Project " link "Menu_Project" 0} - These are general functions like Iconify, Delete File, etc...

  @{" Prefs " link "Menu_Prefs" 0}   - These are various configurable options.

  @{" ARexx " link "Menu_ARexx" 0}   - Allow to execute a script or to record a new one.  Will be 
              disabled if you don't have ARexx installed.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Project" "Menu - Project"

   @{b}Iconify@{ub}

        Closes the main window, and put an AppIcon on the Workbench.
     Files dropped on it will get processed depending on the file(s)
     dropped on it (XPKatana will automatically detect if it must pack or
     unpack it).  If only one file is dropped on it, XPKatana will ask
     your for the destination filename.  If you drop more than one icon,
     then XPKatana will process them keeping the same filenames except if
     "Handle suffix" is enabled.  Double-clicking on the icon will remove
     the AppIcon, and bring back the main window.

   @{b}About@{ub}

        Displays the "About" requester.  Worth checking at least once,
     just to see that cool logo drawn by Phil :)

   @{b}Quit@{ub}

        Closes down XPKatana and exits.
@endnode

@node "Menu_Prefs" "Menu - Preferences"

   @{b}Preferences...@{ub}

        Allow you to configure various options for XPKatana.

     @{b}Task Priority@{ub}

          Allows you to select between three task priority for the 
          (un)packing subprocess:

          @{b}-1@{ub} for background processing (won't slow down other tasks)
           @{b}0@{ub} for regular processing
           @{b}1@{ub} for foreground processing, giving more CPU time to this task


     @{b}Temp Dir@{ub}:

          Select the path where XPKatana will put the temporary files it
          must generate while processing files.  By default, this will be
          @{b}T:@{ub}.

     @{b}Pubscreen@{ub}:

          Select the name of the public screen where XPKatana will open its
          window.  If the public screen can't be found, the Workbench will
          be used as the public screen.

          @{b}NOTE@{ub}: This one will not be saved in the preferences file.
                If you want to make it permanent, you must manualy put it
                in the tooltypes.

     And here are various options which can be toggled on or off:

     @{b}Allow lossy packing@{ub}: If you want to allow the use of a lossy packer
          (shouldn't be activated unless you KNOW what you're doing!)

     @{b}Use password@{ub}: If you want the packer to protect the file against
          unauthorized unpacking by using the specified @{"password" link "Set_Packer_Win" 34} (the
          selected packer must support encryption).

     @{b}Mode step down@{ub}: If you don't have enough memory for the selected packing
          mode, XPK will step down to a lower packmode (when allowed by the
          packer).

     @{b}Handle suffix@{ub}: If you want XPKatana to add an @{b}.xpk@{ub} suffix to the
          filename of files it packs, and remove it from files he unpacked, if
          there's one.

     @{b}Delete source@{ub}: If you want XPKatana to delete the source file when saving
          under a different filename (Process As...)

     @{b}Quiet overwrite@{ub}: If you want XPKatana to quietly overwrite files without
          asking you first.

     @{b}Copy source icon@{ub}: If you want XPKatana to copy the source's icon when
          saving a processed file with a different filename (Process As...)

     @{b}No progress window@{ub}: If you don't want XPKatana to open the progress
          window, in which case the process's status will be shown in the
          status gadget of the main window (if it is opened).  Recommended for
          script operation, as an example.

     @{b}Unpack alien@{ub}: If you try to unpack a file which isn't packed with a
          known XPK packer and you have xfdmaster.library installed on your
          system, then XPkatana will try to unpack it using this library.

     @{b}Use external slaves@{ub}: If you have @{b}Unpack Alien@{ub} enabled, this will tell
          xfdmaster.library to try to use its external unpackers if it can't
          unpack the file with the internal ones.


     And the usual buttons at the bottom:

     @{b}Save@{ub}:   Save the preferences to disk: current packer and
              packmode, password, and all of the options in this window
              except for the public screen name.

     @{b}Use@{ub}:    Use these preferences without saving them (same as
              clicking on the window's close gadget)

     @{b}Cancel@{ub}: Return to the settings that were in use before you
              opened the Preferences window.


   @{b}Load Prefs@{ub}

        Will load the preferences from disk.

   @{b}Save Prefs@{ub}

        Will save the current preferences to disk, like the "Save" button
        in the Preferences window.
@endnode

@node "Menu_ARexx" "Menu - ARexx"
   @{b}Record Script...@{ub}

        Will record an ARexx script to disk.  These scripts allows you
        to automate some repetitive process, or create a batch file to 
        process several files in one shot without the need of having to
        watch the whole process.

        XPKatana will first ask you under which name you wish to save
        it.  By default, the script will be created in the T: directory.  
        This is where you would create temporary scripts which are going to
        be generated just for a single batch processing, while scripts you 
        wish to keep should be created somewhere on disk instead (like in 
        REXX:).  It will then ask you if you want to save the current 
        settings in your script, like the current packer, the state of the 
        current options, etc...

        Then, everything you will do will be logged to the script for
        later playback.  That is, rather than pack a file on "Process", 
        it will write the equivalent ARexx command to the script (that is, 
        "@{"PACK" link "ARexx_PACK" 0}").  Changed flags will be noted to the script to.  And 
        so on.

        Note that while in Script Record mode, you can select more
        than one source file.  The selected files will be put in a file 
        queue, waiting for you to press "Process", where the "@{"SETSOURCE" link "ARexx_SETSOURCE" 0} /
        UN)PACK" commands will be written to the script according to the
        queued filenames, and the queue will be emptied.  Note that if you
        press on "Process As..." rather than "Process" while having a file
        queue, XPKatana will first open a drawer requester, asking you to
        enter the path where the processed files will be written before
        generating the script lines.

        More files may be added to the file queue by clicking on the
        "Source..." button more than once (if you wish to select files from
        more than one directory, as an example).  Useful if you want to do
        a batch processing.

     @{b}Stop Recording@{ub}

        Will stop the recording of an ARexx script, closing it and
        returning to normal operation.  XPKatana will ask you if you wish
        to immediately execute the script you just recorded.

     @{b}Execute Script...@{ub}

        Allow you to launch an ARexx script.  Note than only ONE ARexx
        script can be launched at a time from XPKatana!  Also, you can't 
        record a script while in Execute mode, and vice-versa.
@endnode

@node "ARexx" "ARexx interface"

    XPKatana has an ARexx port named "@{b}KATANA@{ub}", and has many implemented
commands, allowing you to use XPKatana from other applications, or automate
some of its functions.

    To access XPKatana from an ARexx script, you must tell your script to
address the 'KATANA' port.  This is done like this:

    @{b}Address 'KATANA'@{ub}

You must also tell your script to use "RESULT" to obtain informations from
the function:

   @{b}Options Results@{ub}


   @{u}Available Commands:@{uu}

   @{" BEEP         " link "ARexx_BEEP" 0}  -  Will flash the current screen.
   @{" EXAMINE      " link "ARexx_EXAMINE" 0}  -  Examine the current source file.
   @{" GETFLAG      " link "ARexx_GETFLAG" 0}  -  Get the state of an option.
   @{" GETLIBINFO   " link "ARexx_GETLIBINFO" 0}  -  Get an information on current library.
   @{" GETMODEINFO  " link "ARexx_GETMODEINFO" 0}  -  Get an information on current packing mode.
   @{" ICONIFY      " link "ARexx_ICONIFY" 0}  -  Iconify the main window.
   @{" ISPACKED     " link "ARexx_ISPACKED" 0}  -  Tells if the source file is already packed.
   @{" PACK         " link "ARexx_PACK" 0}  -  Pack a file.
   @{" QUIT         " link "ARexx_QUIT" 0}  -  Close down XPKatana.
   @{" REPACK       " link "ARexx_REPACK" 0}  -  Repack a file.
   @{" SETCHUNKSIZE " link "ARexx_SETCHUNKSIZE" 0}  -  Set the chunk's size.
   @{" SETFLAGS     " link "ARexx_SETFLAGS" 0}  -  Configure various options.
   @{" SETPACKER    " link "ARexx_SETPACKER" 0}  -  Select the packer and packing mode.
   @{" SETPASSWORD  " link "ARexx_SETPASSWORD" 0}  -  Set the password for psw-protected processing.
   @{" SETPUBSCREEN " link "ARexx_SETPUBSCREEN" 0}  -  Set the public screen used by the windows.
   @{" SETSOURCE    " link "ARexx_SETSOURCE" 0}  -  Select a source file.
   @{" SETTASKPRI   " link "ARexx_SETTASKPRI" 0}  -  Set the task priority for (un)packing.
   @{" SETTMPDIR    " link "ARexx_SETTMPDIR" 0}  -  Select the directory for temporary files.
   @{" UNICONIFY    " link "ARexx_UNICONIFY" 0}  -  Un-iconify the main window.
   @{" UNPACK       " link "ARexx_UNPACK" 0}  -  Unpack a file.


See the supplied example scripts in the @{i}Rexx/@{ui} drawer, and your ARexx manual
for more informations on how to write ARexx scripts.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_BEEP" "ARexx - BEEP"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Will flash the current screen.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   BEEP

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Will flash the display through the standard DisplayBeep().  Usefull if
wish to warn the user of an error, or that the script has finished its job.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_EXAMINE" "ARexx - EXAMINE"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Examine the current source file.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   EXAMINE

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns a string with the following format:

      @{b}"FILE PACKER ENCRYPTED? RATIO DESCRIPTION"@{ub}

   @{b}FILE@{ub}         is the source filename.
   @{b}PACKER@{ub}       is a four-letters packer, or @{b}#NONE@{ub} if it isn't packed.
   @{b}ENCRYPTED?@{ub}   will be @{b}YES@{ub} or @{b}NO@{ub}, depending if the source file needs 
                a password to be unpacked.
   @{b}RATIO@{ub}        is the compression ratio (if applicable).
   @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}  holds the file type as determined by FileID.library, if 
                installed.

   If the source file couldn't be found, @{b}"NOFILE"@{ub} will be returned.
   If another error occured, @{b}"ERROR"@{ub} will be returned.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_GETFLAG" "ARexx - GETFLAG"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Get the current state of the specified option.  Usefull if you are about
to change the state of some options, but want to be able to restore them to
their initial values afterward.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   GETFLAG [option]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}Option@{ub} is one of these:

   @{b}ALIEN@{ub}       - Enable usage of xfdmaster.library to unpack files packed
                 with alien packers (non-XPK).
   @{b}ALIENEXTERN@{ub} - Enable the use of the external slaves if you're using
                 xfdmaster.library (see @{b}ALIEN@{ub}).
   @{b}ALLOWLOSSY@{ub}  - Allow lossy packers.
   @{b}COPYICON@{ub}    - Will copy the source's icon with the destination.
   @{b}DELSOURCE@{ub}   - Will delete the source file after processing.
   @{b}NOPROGRESS@{ub}  - Won't open the progress window while processing.
   @{b}OVERWRITE@{ub}   - Will quietly overwrite destination if it already exists.
   @{b}STEPDOWN@{ub}    - Allow the packer to do a mode step-down when needed.
   @{b}SUFFIX@{ub}      - Will take care of the .xpk suffix, adding/removing it
                 to the destination file as appropriate.
   @{b}USEPASSWORD@{ub} - Enables password protection, if the packer supports it.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Will return '@{b}0@{ub}' if the option is disabled, '@{b}1@{ub}' if it's enabled, and
'@{b}ERROR@{ub}' if the option is unknown.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_ICONIFY" "ARexx - ICONIFY"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   XPKatana will close its window and put an @{"AppIcon" link "Menu_Project" 7} on the Workbench. 

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   ICONIFY

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

  None.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_QUIT" "ARexx - QUIT"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Shutdown XPKatana.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   QUIT

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Around 80 Kb of free memory :)
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETSOURCE" "ARexx - SETSOURCE"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Select the source file.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   SETSOURCE [source]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}SOURCE@{ub} is the source file.  If you use @{b}"?"@{ub} as the source, a file
requester will be opened, asking for a source file.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}ERROR@{ub} if no argument was supplied.  
   @{b}NOFILE@{ub} if the selected file couldn't be found (note that XPKatana 
          will still keep that filename as the source).

@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETTASKPRI" "ARexx - SETTASKPRI"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Select the task priority of the packing sub-process.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   SETTASKPRI [priority]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}PRIORITY@{ub} is one of the following keywords:

        @{b}LOW@{ub}   - Task priority of -1 (in background)
        @{b}NORM@{ub}  - Task priority of 0 (same as a normal process)
        @{b}HIGH@{ub}  - Task priority of 1 (gives more priority to it)

   Usualy, leaving this to "NORM" should be enough for most needs.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns @{b}ERROR@{ub} if an invalid priority has been supplied, in which case the
priority will remain unchanged.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETFLAGS" "ARexx - SETFLAGS"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Set various options of XPkatana.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   SETFLAGS [option_1] [state] [option_2] [state] ... [option_x] [state]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   Any number of these options can be used:

   @{b}ALIEN@{ub}       - Enable usage of xfdmaster.library to unpack files packed
                 with alien packers (non-XPK).
   @{b}ALIENEXTERN@{ub} - Enable the use of the external slaves if you're using
                 xfdmaster.library (see @{b}ALIEN@{ub}).
   @{b}ALLOWLOSSY@{ub}  - Allow lossy packers.
   @{b}COPYICON@{ub}    - Will copy the source's icon with the destination.
   @{b}DELSOURCE@{ub}   - Will delete the source file after processing.
   @{b}NOPROGRESS@{ub}  - Won't open the progress window while processing.
   @{b}OVERWRITE@{ub}   - Will quietly overwrite destination if it already exists.
   @{b}STEPDOWN@{ub}    - Allow the packer to do a mode step-down when needed.
   @{b}SUFFIX@{ub}      - Will take care of the .xpk suffix, adding/removing it
                 to the destination file as appropriate.
   @{b}USEPASSWORD@{ub} - Enables password protection, if the packer supports it.

  Each options must be followed by a state flag:

     @{b}0@{ub} - Disabled.
     @{b}1@{ub} - Enabled.

@{b}@{u}Example:@{ub}@{uu}

     SETFLAGS USEPASSWORD 0 SUFFIX 1 DELSOURCE 1

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

  None.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_GETLIBINFO" "ARexx - GETLIBINFO"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Return informations on the current packer.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   GETLIBINFO [info]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}INFO@{ub} is one of the following values:

      @{b}1@{ub} - The packer's short name.
      @{b}2@{ub} - The packer's complete name.
      @{b}3@{ub} - A one line description of the packer.
      @{b}4@{ub} - Returns a formatted string, with some features about 
          the current packer.  The string has the following format:

         "ENCRYPT <flag> NEEDPASSWORD <flag> MODES <flag> LOSSY <flag>"

            @{b}ENCRYPT:@{ub}      Does this packer supports encryption?
            @{b}NEEDPASSWORD:@{ub} Does this packer REQUIRES a password?
            @{b}MODES:@{ub}        Does this packer supports more than one packing
                          mode?
            @{b}LOSSY:@{ub}        Does this packer do lossy compression?

           <Flag> is either "@{b}YES@{ub}" or "@{b}NO@{ub}".

      @{b}5@{ub} - The largest chunk size for input (in bytes).
      @{b}6@{ub} - The default chunk size for input (in bytes).
      @{b}7@{ub} - The default packing mode (between 0 and 100).

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns a string according to the supplied argument, or "@{b}ERROR@{ub}" if the
   argument was invalid.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_GETMODEINFO" "ARexx - GETMODEINFO"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Return informations on the current packing mode.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   GETMODEINFO [info]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}INFO@{ub} is one of the following values:

        @{b}1@{ub} - The current packmode (between 0 and 100)
        @{b}2@{ub} - The description of the current mode.
        @{b}3@{ub} - Memory needed for packing (usualy in bytes).
        @{b}4@{ub} - Memory needed for unpacking (usualy in bytes).
        @{b}5@{ub} - Average packing speed in Kb/s (usualy on an A3000/030)
        @{b}6@{ub} - Average unpacking speed in Kb/s (usualy on an A3000/030)
        @{b}7@{ub} - Average compression ratio (on an AmigaVision data file).
        @{b}8@{ub} - Desired chunk size (in Kb) for this mode.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns a string according to the supplied argument, or "@{b}ERROR@{ub}" if the
   argument was invalid.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_ISPACKED" "ARexx - ISPACKED"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Says if the current source file is packed with a known XPK packer.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   ISPACKED

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns @{b}"1"@{ub} if the file is packed with a known XPK packer, @{b}"0"@{ub} if it
ain't, or @{b}"ERROR"@{ub} if an error occured (no source file, source doesn't exist,
etc...)
@endnode

@node "ARexx_PACK" "ARexx - PACK"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Compress a file.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   PACK [destination]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}DESTINATION:@{ub} An optional destination filename.  If omitted, the 
                destination will be the same as the source, with a ".xpk"
                suffix added if the "Handle Suffix" option is enabled.  

                If @{b}"?"@{ub} is supplied as the filename, a filerequester will 
                be opened, asking for the destination filename.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns "@{b}ABORT@{ub}" if the packing was aborted by the user or an error.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_REPACK" "ARexx - REPACK"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Uncompress a file if it's already packed, and recompress it with the
selected packer.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   REPACK [destination]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}DESTINATION:@{ub} An optional destination filename.  If omitted, the 
                destination will be the same as the source, with a ".xpk"
                suffix added if the "Handle Suffix" option is enabled.  

                If @{b}"?"@{ub} is supplied as the filename, a filerequester will 
                be opened, asking for the destination filename.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns "@{b}ABORT@{ub}" if the repacking was aborted by the user or an error.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETPASSWORD" "ARexx - SETPASSWORD"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Select a password for (un)packing encrypted files.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   SETPASSWORD [password]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   The password to use for (un)packing encrypted files.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}ERROR@{ub} if no password has been specified.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETCHUNKSIZE" "ARexx - SETCHUNKSIZE"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Set the file's packing chunk size.

   IMPORTANT: The chunk size will get resetted to the packer's default 
              size each time you select a new packer!  So you must use 
              this function AFTER selecting the packer (via SETPACKER or 
              the GUI).

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   SETCHUNKSIZE [chunksize]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}CHUNKSIZE@{ub} is the size of each blocks of data in the packed file, given
             in bytes.  It will also determine how often the progress 
             window will be updated (that is, each time a chunk has been 
             (un)packed).  The chunk size must be between 10 and the 
             packer's max chunk size.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Will return "@{b}ERROR@{ub}" if no value was supplied.  If the value doesn't fit
between 10 and "max chunk size", it will get adjusted to fit in these
limits.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETPACKER" "ARexx - SETPACKER"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Set the packer and packing mode.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   SETPACKER [packer] [packmode]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

  @{b}PACKER@{ub} is the 4-letters XPK packer to use (like "NUKE").
  @{b}PACKMODE@{ub} is the packing mode, between 0 and 100.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns @{b}"OK"@{ub}, or @{b}"BADMODE"@{ub} if the packing mode is outside of the 0-100 
   range, @{b}"BADPACKER"@{ub} if the specified packer isn't present on the system.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETPUBSCREEN" "ARexx - SETPUBSCREEN"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

Select the public screen on which XPKatana will open its windows.  If
XPKatana was opened, then the window will be closed, and re-opened on the
specified screen.

If the requested screen can't be found, the Workbench screen will be used
instead.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   SETPUBSCREEN [screen]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}SCREEN:@{ub}  The name of the public screen on which the windows and 
            requesters will be opened.

            NOTE: Public screen names are case sensitive.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns "@{b}ERROR@{ub}" if no public screen name has been given, or if the
requested screen can't be locked.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_SETTMPDIR" "ARexx - SETTMPDIR"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

Select the directory where XPKatana will put its temporary files.  Usually,
you would keep that to "T:", but this command allow you to relocate it
elsewhere on your hard disk if needed (like if you need more space).

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   SETTMPDIR [path]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}PATH:@{ub}  The path where the temporary files will be created.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns "@{b}ERROR@{ub}" if the requested path can't be found or if no path is
specified.  In such a case, the previous path will be kept.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_UNICONIFY" "ARexx - UNICONIFY"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   If XPKatana was in an iconify state, will remove the appicon and re-open
the main window.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu}

   UNICONIFY

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   None.
@endnode

@node "ARexx_UNPACK" "ARexx - UNPACK"
@{b}@{u}Description:@{ub}@{uu}

   Uncompress a file.

@{b}@{u}Template:@{ub}@{uu} 

   UNPACK [destination]

@{b}@{u}Input:@{ub}@{uu}

   @{b}DESTINATION:@{ub} An optional destination filename.  If omitted, the 
                destination will be the same as the source, with the
                ".xpk" suffix removed if there's one and the 
                "Handle Suffix" option is enabled. 

                If @{b}"?"@{ub} is supplied as the destination, a filerequester 
                will be opened, asking for a destination filename.

@{b}@{u}Result:@{ub}@{uu}

   Returns "@{b}ABORT@{ub}" if the unpacking was aborted by the user or an error,
   or if the file wasn't packed with any known packer.
@endnode

@node "Legal_Stuff" "Legal Stuff"

    Except where otherwise indicated, all files in this distribution are
Copyright © 1996-2000 Victor Ducedre.  All Rights Reserved.  This complete
and unchanged archive is freely redistributable, except as noted below.

    Parts of this documentation have not changed from previous versions,
and were written by Eric Sauvageau.

    This package is offered as Shareware.  If you're using XPKatana and like
it, then I ask you to send me a fee of $10 US.  I will also accept things
like a registered version of another program (your own, not somebody else's!
:-) as an alternative.

    You cannot resell this program for profit, but inclusion on CD-ROMs,
PD collections or coverdisks is allowed.  The only thing I ask is that if
you include it on some magazine coverdisk, that you send me a free issue of
the magazine with the coverdisk.

    As you can see, the program isn't crippled in any way.  You won't receive
a keyfile in exchange for the payment.  This is because I don't believe in
crippleware.  I @{u}HATE@{uu} it when I download a program only to find it to be
crippled to the point of uselessness.  So, why should you register?

    The Amiga's future relies heavily on Freeware and Shareware developers,
because most of the largest commercial developers seem to ignore the Amiga.
Many Shareware developers ends up being hired by Amiga dedicated ciesą,
giving you even better software.   So, supporting us is an excellent way of
concretely supporting @{b}YOUR@{ub} Amiga.  Also I usually re-invest shareware fees I
receive by registering other shareware or by buying Amiga hardware or
commercial software.  So, it makes it twice a good investment for the Amiga
community :)

    @{"FileID.library" link "About_FileID" 0} is written by Oliver Lange, and is Public Domain.

    Xpkmaster.library and the associated packers are written by Dirk Stoecker
and various other authors, and are Freeware.

    @{"Xfdmaster.library" link "About_Xfdmaster" 0} is written by Dirk Stoecker, and is Freeware.

    I'm am not responsible for any data loss, or any kind of problem
encountered while using this package.  You're using it at @{i}your own risks@{ui}, so
if you find a bug that I didn't noticed before release, if your girlfriend
starts blowing smoke or your computer slaps you and dumps you for being a
moron, it's not my fault.  If you do find a bug, please report it so I can
fix it in a future release.

ą - I have no idea what Eric meant when he wrote 'cies'.  But it only took
me two years to notice it.
@endnode

